summary: This module provides the capability to connect with NATS and NATS Streaming servers and performs the below functionalities.
description:
Module Overview

This module provides the capability to connect with NATS and NATS Streaming servers and performs the below functionalities.

  • Point to point communication (Queues)
  • Pub/Sub (Topics)
  • Request/Reply

Basic Usage

Setting up the connection

First step is setting up the connection with the NATS Basic/Streaming server. The following ways can be used to connect to a NATS Basic/Streaming server.

  1. Connect to a server using the URL
nats:Connection connection = new("nats://localhost:4222");
  1. Connect to one or more servers with a custom configuration
nats:Connection connection = new("nats://serverone:4222, nats://servertwo:4222",  config);

Publishing messages

Publishing messages is handled differently in the NATS Basic server and Streaming server. The 'ballerina/nats' module provides different APIs to publish messages to each server.

Publishing messages to the NATS basic server

Once connected, publishing is accomplished via one of the below two methods.

  1. Publish with the subject and the message content.
nats:Producer producer = new(connection);
nats:Error? result = producer->publish(subject, "hello world");
  1. Publish as a request that expects a reply.
nats:Producer producer = new(connection);
nats:Message|nats:Error reqReply = producer->request(subject, "hello world", 5000);
  1. Publish messages with a replyTo subject
nats:Producer producer = new(connection);
nats:Error? result = producer->publish(subject, <@untainted>message, 
                         replyToSubject);
  1. Publish messages with a replyTo callback service
nats:Producer producer = new(connection);
nats:Error? result = producer->publish(subject, <@untainted>message, 
                         replyToService);

service replyToService =
@nats:SubscriptionConfig {
    subject: "replySubject"
}
service {

    resource function onMessage(nats:Message msg, string data) {
    }

    resource function onError(nats:Message msg, nats:Error err) {
    }
};

Publishing messages to a NATS streaming server

Once connected to a streaming server, publishing messages is accomplished using the following method.

nats:StreamingProducer producer = new(connection);
string|error result = producer->publish(subject, "hello world");

Publish api supports the byte[], boolean, string, int, float, decimal, xml, json, record {} message types.

Listening to incoming messages

The Ballerina NATS module provides the following mechanisms to listen to messages. Similar to message publishing, listening to messages is also handled differently in the NATS basic and streaming servers.

Listening to messages from a NATS server

// Initializes the NATS listener.
listener nats:Listener subscription = new(connection);

// Binds the consumer to listen to the messages published to the 'demo' subject.
@nats:SubscriptionConfig {
    subject: "demo"
}
service demo on subscription {

    resource function onMessage(nats:Message msg, string data) {
    }

    resource function onError(nats:Message msg, nats:Error err) {
    }
}

Listening to messages from a Streaming server

// Initializes the NATS Streaming listener.
listener nats:StreamingListener subscription = new(conn, "test-cluster", "c1");

// Binds the consumer to listen to the messages published to the 'demo' subject.
@nats:StreamingSubscriptionConfig {
    subject: "demo"
}
service demo on subscription {

    resource function onMessage(nats:StreamingMessage msg, string data) {
    }

    resource function onError(nats:StreamingMessage msg, nats:Error err) {
    }

}

Advanced Usage

Using the TLS protocol

The Ballerina NATS module allows the use of the tls:// protocol in its URLs. This setting expects a secure socket to be set in the connection configuration as shown below.

nats:ConnectionConfig config = {
    secureSocket : {
        trustStore : {
            path: "nats-basic/keyStore.p12",
            password: "xxxxx"
        }
    }
};

// Initializes a connection.
nats:Connection connection = new("tls://localhost:4222", config = config);

Note: The default thread pool size used in Ballerina is the number of processors available * 2. You can configure the thread pool size by using the BALLERINA_MAX_POOL_SIZE environment variable.

For information on the operations, which you can perform with this module, see the below Functions.

For examples on the usage of the connector, see the following.

  • Basic Publisher and Subscriber Example.
  • Basic Streaming Publisher and Subscriber Example
  • Streaming Publisher and Subscriber With Data Binding Example
  • Durable Subscriptions Example
  • Queue Groups Example
  • Historical Message Replay Example

fields.name: connectionName
fields.description: Name of the connection (this is optional)

fields.name: maxReconnect
fields.description: Maximum number of reconnect attempts. The reconnect state is triggered when an already established connection is lost. During the initial connection attempt, the client will cycle over its server list one time regardless of the maxReconnects value that is set. Use 0 to turn off auto reconnecting. Use -1 to turn on infinite reconnects.

fields.name: reconnectWaitInSeconds
fields.description: The time(in seconds) to wait between the reconnect attempts to reconnect to the same server

fields.name: connectionTimeoutInSeconds
fields.description: The timeout (in seconds) for the connection attempts

fields.name: pingIntervalInMinutes
fields.description: The interval (in minutes) between the attempts of pinging the server

fields.name: maxPingsOut
fields.description: The maximum number of pings the client can have in flight. The default value is two

fields.name: username
fields.description: The username for basic authentication

fields.name: password
fields.description: The password for basic authentication

fields.name: token
fields.description: The token for token-based authentication

fields.name: inboxPrefix
fields.description: The connection's inbox prefix, which all inboxes will start with

fields.name: noEcho
fields.description: Turns off echoing. This prevents the server from echoing messages back to the connection if it has subscriptions on the subject being published to

fields.name: enableErrorListener
fields.description: Enables the connection to the error listener

fields.name: secureSocket
fields.description: Configurations related to SSL/TLS

records.name: ConnectionConfig
records.description: Configurations related to creating a NATS streaming subscription.

fields.name: maxMessages
fields.description: Maximum number of pending messages retrieved and held by the consumer service. The default value is 65536

fields.name: maxBytes
fields.description: Total size of pending messages in bytes retrieved and held by the consumer service. The default value is 67108864

records.name: PendingLimits
records.description: The configurations to set limits on the maximum number of messages or maximum size of messages this consumer will hold before it starts to drop new messages waiting for the resource functions to drain the queue. Setting a value less than or equal to 0 will disable this check.

fields.name: trustStore
fields.description: Configurations associated with the TrustStore

fields.name: keyStore
fields.description: Configurations associated with the KeyStore

fields.name: protocol
fields.description: The standard name of the requested protocol

records.name: SecureSocket
records.description: Configurations related to facilitating a secure communication with a remote HTTP endpoint.

fields.name: ackTimeoutInSeconds
fields.description: Timeout (in seconds) to wait for an acknowledgement for the corresponding subscription

fields.name: connectionTimeoutInSeconds
fields.description: Timeout (in seconds) to wait for a connection

fields.name: maxPubAcksInFlight
fields.description: The maximum number of publish ACKs that may be in flight at any point of time

fields.name: discoverPrefix
fields.description: Subject prefix used for server discovery

records.name: StreamingConfig
records.description: Configuration related to establishing a streaming connection.

fields.name: subject
fields.description: Name of the subject to which it is subscribed to

fields.name: queueName
fields.description: The name of the queue group to which the subscription belongs to

fields.name: durableName
fields.description: If set, this will survive client restarts

fields.name: maxInFlight
fields.description: The number of messages the cluster will have in-flight without an ACK

fields.name: ackWaitInSeconds
fields.description: The time (in seconds) the cluster will wait for an ACK for a given message

fields.name: subscriptionTimeoutInSeconds
fields.description: The time (in seconds) the subscription will wait if a network failure occurs during the creation of it

fields.name: manualAck
fields.description: Enables manual acknowledgments

fields.name: startPosition
fields.description: The position to start receiving messages

records.name: StreamingSubscriptionConfigData
records.description: The configurations for the NATS streaming subscription.

fields.name: subject
fields.description: Name of the subject

fields.name: queueName
fields.description: Name of the queue group

fields.name: pendingLimits
fields.description: Parameters to set limits on the maximum number of pending messages or maximum size of pending messages

constants.description: Specifies that message delivery should begin with the oldest available message for this subject.
